INSERT INTO `topics` (`id`, `subject_id`, `topic_name`, `introduction`, `objectives`, `content`, `possible_questions`, `real_life_application`, `summary`, `formulas`, `visibility`, `logo`) VALUES
(1, 5, 'ABIOTIC / BIOTIC FACTORS', '<h3><b>INTRODUCTION:</b></h3><br/>\r\n<p> Abiotic factors are the non-living that interacts with the living (biotic) in their natural environment. Example are temperature, rainfall, light, hydrogen ion concentration (PH value), wind pressure etc. <br/>\r\nAbiotic factors determine the kind of biotic community that is found on a habitat. Some of these factors are important to most habitats, while others are uniquely important to a specific habitat such as terrestrial habitat or an aquatic type. <br/>\r\nThere are many factors that are common to the two contrasting habitats (terrestrial and aquatic). They include temperature, rainfall, light intensity, hydrogen ion concentration (PH value), winds and pressure. Of these factors, temperature and rainfall determine the setting of the community.</p><br/>', '<p>at the end of the lesson, you should be able to</p><br/>\r\n<ol>\r\n<li>Explain Abiotic/Biotic factors.</li>\r\n<li>List factors common to all habitats.</li>\r\n<li>Write short note on the factors affecting aquatic habitat.</li>\r\n<li>List the factors affecting terrestrial habitat.</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n<br/>\r\n', '<p>An Abiotic is the non-living that interacts with the living (biotic) in their dwelling environment. Some biotic factors may affect an organism in many ways. For example, when competitors, parasites, prey, or symbionts are in abundance with time, the relationship between the Abiotic and biotic may be affected if the available resource such as water, food, mates, and shelter can no longer support the biotic i.e. plant and animals.</p><br/>\r\n<p>Temperature, rainfall, height light intensity, hydrogen ion concentration (PH value), wind and pressure are the factors that are common to all habitats, but temperature rainfall determine the major brome (a community that is characterized by a dominant type of vegetation) such tropical rainfall, rainforest, grassland, desert and tundra of the world.</p></p>\r\n<h3><b>Temperature:</b> </h3><br/><p>it is one of the climate factors that is common to both terrestrial and aquatic habitats. But terrestrial habitats show a higher temperature range than aquatic ones. In temperature countries, there are seasonal temperature difference ranges. In winter the temperature is below O0C and above 200c in summer. In the tropic lower temperature are usually recorded during wet season and lower during dry season. In West Africa during the harmattan, a cool wind, blows and lower temperatures are recorded.</p><br/>\r\n<p>In aquatic habitats, temperature decrease with depth. For instance, in marine water bodies, the depth is 1500m is 40C but the temperature at the surface is 300C. on the other hand decrease in height, there is always a drop of 10C for every 150m rise above sea level.</p><br/>\r\n<p>Most organism cannot withstand high temperature because at higher temperature, they are killed, at lower temperature, they are inactive; and at optimum temperatures they grow and reproduce rapidly. Some animal show adaptation that allow that allow them to live at low temperature and high temperature such as hibernation and aestivation in the temperature and arctic region respectively. When temperature are favorable for life, there is variation in such biotic set up (plants and animals) with very large communities.</p><br/>\r\n<h3><b>Rainfall:</b> </h3><br/><p>Its is the most important factors that affect the biotic community of a terrestrial habitat. For example, an annual rainfall of 1800mm, result in a luxuriant rainforest, while an unreliable annual rainfall below 250mm result into barren desert. Reason, is that water is life and the main consistent of living organism.</p><br/>\r\n<b>Light intensity:</b> <p>Light is very important for photosynthesis to take place and plants cannot grow in the dark. Likewise some organism are affected by the distribution of light, some are light by others are shade-tolerant species</p>.<br/>\r\n<h3><b>Hydrogen ion concentration (PH value) :</b></h3><br/><p>Is given by Ph value, it is a scale use in expressing the acidity or alkalinity of a solution which range from 1 to 14, with PH 1 is very acidity, Ph 7 is neutral while PH 14, is very alkalinity.</p><br/>\r\n<p>Most soils have PH ranges of 4.5 (strongly acidic) and such soil is good for rice production while some soil have 8.3 PH which is fairly alkaline which support the major crop productions. Some organism such as fresh water molecule cannot withstand PH value less than 6.5 PH, they are usually absent from freshwater medium. Most plants thrive well in neutral or slightly alkaline soil but ascorbic soil support very little crop e.g rice.</p><br/>\r\n<h3><b>Wind: </b></h3><br/><p>Air in motion is termed wind and winds are important to habitats (aquatic and terrestrial) because they cause water current and waves, and also carry rain bearing cloud. In West Africa, Nigeria winds influence the climate, wind causing the dry harmattan from the Sahara causing the dry season and a rain bearing south-westerly  winds from the ocean causing a numeral rainy season. The winds are responsible for;</p><br/>\r\n<ol>\r\n<li>The local brome such as rainforest, grassland. </li>\r\n<li>Winds help in the dispersal of fruit and seeds and cause pollination in some plants such as grasses.</li>\r\n<li>The drying effect of strong winds cause high transpiration (loss of water vapour form the plant) rates which affect the types of plant that are formed in the regions exposed to such conditions.</li>\r\n<li>Insect spread faster in the direction of winds in a given area even though the other direction offered the same opportunity for their establishment.</li></ol><br/>\r\n<h3><b>Pressure:</b> </h3><br/><p>In the ocean pressure varies from the depth of the ocean to the highest altitudes of the atmosphere. Atmosphere pressure increase as we go down the sea level. In the oceans, the pressure increase by 1.03kg/m2 in every 10m. Organisms found living at depth of about 400m live in conditions of abundance pressure and are well adapted to such condition since they cannot survive at the surface waters where the pressure is much lower.</p><br/>\r\n<h3><b>Step III</b></h3><br/>\r\n<p>Some biotic organisms (plants and animals) are structurally adapted to live in aquatic meelia. For instance, fishes are able to dwell in water due to the presence of fins that enable them to swim, whales, sharks are able to line water due to the possession of flippers and some plant have sticky bodies, reduced cuticles, well developed air space (for the supply for oxygen) that equally enable them to dwell in aquatic medium.</p><br/>\r\n<p>There some factors those only operate in such habitat. Examples of the factors are as follows:</p><br/> <ol>\r\n<li>Salinity</li>\r\n<li>Density</li>\r\n<li>Turbidity</li>\r\n<li>Current or water waves, tidal movement and waves</li>\r\n<li>Dissolved gases</li>\r\n<li>Nature of the substratum </li></ol><br/>\r\n<h3><b>SALINITY:</b></h3><br/>\r\n<p>Salinity is concentration of dissolved salts in water. The rate of salinity is very high in sea water but very low in freshwater meaning sea water is salty but in brackish water (sea water and freshwater mixed together to form brackish). At the mouths and swamps of brackish water, salinity charges with tides.</p><br/>\r\n<p>Aquatic organism have homeostatic behavior to main the emetic balance between their internal and external environment as shown below</p><br/>\r\n<ol>\r\n<li>Organisms living in water have the adaptation for bringing the excess water from their bodies.</li>\r\n<li>Sea water organisms have no problem because the sea is almost the same with their internal environment and</li>\r\n<li>Those living in brackish water have tissues that tolerate changes in the concentration of salts in their body fluid.</li></ol>\r\n<h3><b>DENSITY:</b></h3><br/>\r\n<p>Air is less dense than water. Hence, its easier to move through air than water. The density of freshwater is less dense than that of sea water. Aquatic organisms generally have streamlined body to help them move easily in water. Some organisms such as water lily has reduced cuticle that enable it to float at the surface of the water and it is also sensitive to changes in density. Eggs of aquatic organism sink to different depth. According to the density of the water because freshwater, sea water and brackish water bodies have different densities.</p><br/>\r\n<h3><b>TURBIDITY</b></h3><br/>\r\n<p>Clean water has a very low turbidity while unclean water has high turbidity and turbidity is caused by the suspended matter in water. In low turbid water, light penetrate to a greater depth below water surface which enable photosynthetic organisms such as phyplankton (spirogyra) to manufacture its food.</p><br/>\r\n<p>In freshwater which is less dense, its turbidity increases during raining season as a result of debris is washed from the soil into the water bodies.</p><br/>\r\n<h3><b>CURRENT OR WATER FLOW</b></h3><br/>\r\n<p>water current are mainly common in aquatic ecosystems. During raining season, fast current occur in river and stream but in ponds, lakes, sea etc water currents are mainly due to different in temperature between the upper and the lower part of a water body because the water body is not moving or flowing. Water current increase aeration (pores that allow oxygen to penetrate), increase the turbidity of water and carry warm water to colder regions which affect the distribution of aquatic organisms.</p><br/>\r\n<p>Water current affect most organisms found in an aquatic medium / habitat due to the speed of the water flow. For instance, animals living in fast moving water bodies have some structure for attaching themselves to the rocks or substratum so that they cannot be swept away.</p><br/>\r\n<h3><b>TIDAL MOVEMENT AND WAVES</b></h3><br/>\r\n<p>They affect the Abiotic community dwelling in the intertidal zones of the seashore and river month. They exposed to tidal movements twice. Wave action is a result of various rate of air movement which affects most organisms living in the intertidal zones and seashores. Most of the organisms are attached to substratum for been swept away by waves or live in burrows. And some have hard body covering to prevent evaporation of water from their bodies. </p><br/>\r\n<p>Waves cause aeration of the surface waters in the open sea which enable aquatic organisms to have a enough supply of dissolved gases for their needs such as oxygen (O2), carbon dioxide (CO2), O2 for the aquatic animals and CO2 for the plants.<p><br/>\r\n<h3><b>DISSOLVED GASES</b></h3><br/>\r\n<p>Both aquatic plants and animals need dissolve CO2 and O2 to carry out photosynthesis and cellular respiration respectively. O2 concentration decreases with increase in the depth of water i.e O2 is more abundant at the surface of the water. The presence of organic matter and high temperatures reduce the oxygen content of water. These factors affect organism dwelling in the aquatic medium, organism dwelling in the deep and bottom water bodies are specially adapted for living in water with low O2 concentration.</p>\r\n<h3><b>NATURE OF THE SUBSTRUM </b></h3><br/>\r\n<p>Sub-strum is the floor of the water bodies. It may be rocky or muddy which affect the kindâ€™s organisms. Generally, a muddy floor has a higher organic content from the sandy or the rocky types. As a result, more organisms live in a muddy substratum provided that O2 supply is sufficient. Burrow animals such as earthworms are usually found in swift-flowing streams and animals dwelling in such floors have structures that enable them to hold onto the rocky surface so as to prevent them from being swept away since it is a running water bodies.</p><br/>\r\n<h3><b>Step IV</b></h3><br/>\r\n<p>The land is the major dwelling habitat of the biotic community and the main factors of terrestrial habitat are;</p><br/>\r\n<ol>\r\n<li>The land surface and the soil</li><br/>\r\n<li>Relative humidity</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n<h3><b>LAND SURFACE</b></h3><br/>\r\n<p>The land surface is responsible for variation in the vegetation of a place because it may be flat or sloping. For instance, a land in the tropic may have forest vegetation at its base and an acrospires vegetation near its peak. The slop may be steep  and its gradient affect the growth of organisms and its also encourage fast running water and therefore, encourages erosion which result in shallow and infertile soil which result to low yield of crops grown and few animals reared. But in gentle slopes, the flow of surface water is slow, erosion is minimized, and enough water is available to plants and animals which increase the biotic organisms present on such slopes.</p><br/><br/>\r\n<h3><b>SOIL </b></h3><br/>\r\n<p>Soil determines the vegetation of region. Regions with similar climates have variation in the type of plants due to soil differences. The types of soil are influenced by temperature and rainfall. Heavy rainfall causes leaching the washing away of soluble minerals to deep area that is out of reach of plant. And high temperature increases the rate of decomposition of organic matter into the soil, thereby lowering its humus contents. Hence, poor soil in the tropic is as a result of bad climatic condition and good soils in the temperature are as a result of good climatic condition.</p><br/>\r\n\r\n<h3><b>RELATIVE HUMIDITY</b></h3><br/>\r\n<p>It is the amount of moisture in the air. It is usually high in hot wet regions. It affects the rate of water vapour from the body surfaces of the organisms. A low humidity causes high water loss. Organisms living in a place of low humidity must possess a structure that reduces water loss. For instance, plants in the desert like cacti have reduced spines to prevent water los and camel mainly found in the desert conserve water in their bodies to prevent water loss.</p><br/>\r\n', '<ol>\r\n<li>Explain the following factors affecting an aquatic habitat in details. </li>\r\n<ul type=â€œletterâ€>\r\n<li>Rainfall</li>\r\n<li>Wind</li>\r\n<li>Turbidity</li>\r\n<li>Pressure</li></ul>\r\n<li>Write short note on the following.</li>\r\n<ul type=â€œletterâ€ >\r\n<li>Salinity</li>\r\n<li>Density</li>\r\n<li>Relative humidity</li>\r\n<li>Soil</li></ul>\r\n<li>Explain briefly on how important is temperature and rainfall to living organisms.</li>\r\n</ol><br/>\r\n', '', '<h3><b>SUMMARY</b></h3>\r\n<p>Abiotic factor are the non-living in the environment whole biotic are the living that interact with the Abiotic in their natural environment. There are many factors affecting the two contrasting habitats such as temperature, rainfall, wind etc.</p><br/>\r\n<p>Therefore are specific factors that affect the Abiotic such as turbidity, water currents, and relative humidity affects the terrestrial habitats. Among all the factors that affect the two habitats are temperature and rainfall. Optimum temperature favour growth and reproduction while enough rainfall also favour the growth and reproduction of both plants and animals.</p>', '', 1, ''),
(2, 5, 'ECOSYSTEM', '<p>An ecosystem can be defined as a fractional unit in nature and it is made up of biotic and abiotic components. The interaction between biotic and abiotic components. The interaction between biotic and abiotic components resulting in the ecosystem being a functional unit.</p><br/>\r\n  ', '<p>at the end of lesson, the student should be able to:</p><br/>\r\n<ol>\r\n<li>Define an ecosystem witth examples</li>\r\n<li>List the three components of an ecosystem and explain autotrophs.</li>\r\n<li>Explain the heterotrophs and thier functions.</li>\r\n<li>Explain the decomposers using examples.</li></ol>\r\n  ', '<h3>Biotic factor:</h3><br/><p>it includes plants and animals. The biotic factor can be divided into two phases, namely:</p><br/>\r\n<ol>\r\n<li>Biotic resources which include nutrients and inorganic substance such as nitrogen, phosphorus, potassium, carbon, etc.</li><br/>\r\n<li>Biotic Condition: it includes sunlight, which is the primary source of energy.</li>\r\n</ol><br/>\r\n<h3>Abiotic factors:</h3><br/> <p>examples of abiotic factors are: rainfall, temperature, humidity, hydrogen ion concentration.</p><br/>\r\n<p>In a community set-up which is defined as a naturally occuring place where plants and animals dwell have effect on the abiotic factors. E.g rainfall, temperature, wind, etc. because the interaction between the two factors are shown by their feeding relationships. Food producers(plants) use the sunâ€™s energy and nutrients from the abiotic environment to make food. The energy and nutrient in this food is passed on to:</p><br/>\r\n<ol>\r\n<li>Heterotrophs and</li><br/>\r\n<li>The decomposers</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n<h3>Heterotrophs:</h3><br/>\r\n<p> they are organisms that depend on autotrophs(plants) for their food. They feed directly or indirectly. Those that feed directly from the plants are called herbivores e.g cows, goats, sheep, etc. and hence they are called primary consumers while those that feed on primary consumers are called canivorous animals ( secondary consumers) and those taht feed on secondary consumers are called tetiary consumers. Examples are bacteria and fungi.</p><br/>\r\n<p>The above processes occured when they feed from one another. The food they feed on cannot be re-cycled or re-used because it escaped as heat energy but the nutrients can be re-used again by the producers because it is released into the environment. Thus, an ecosystem is actually a functional unit.</p><br/>\r\n<h2><u><b>An ecosystem</b></u></h2><br/>\r\n<p>An ecosystem is a functional or self supporting unit in nature. It is made up of living things i.e(plants and animals) and the non-living components i.e(sunlight, water, humidity, temperature, etc.) and the interaction between the living things with their non-living resulting in an ecosystem.</p> <br/>\r\n<p>An ecosystem is said to be a functional unit because of two important reasons as indicated below:</p><br/>\r\n<ol>\r\n<li>Energy is lost which cannot be recycled, hence food chain is one direction.</li><br/>\r\n<li>Nutrients can be recycled or re-used because if a lion which is the secondary consumer eventually dies, tetiary consumers(bacteria and fungi) acted upon it and the decomposed body supply nutrients to the antotrophs(plants)</li>\r\n</ol>\r\nDIAGRAM\r\n<h2><u><b>Component of an ecosystem</b></u></h2><br/>\r\n<p>There are three major component of an ecosystem namely:</p>\r\n<ol>\r\n<li>Anto trophs</li>\r\n<li>Heterotrophs</li>\r\n<li>Decomposers</li>\r\n</ol><br/>\r\n<h3>Antotrophs:</h3><br/><p> they are organisms that are able to use sunlight or chemical energy to manufacture their own food from simple inorganic substances. Hence, they are called primary producers. There are two types of producers;</p><br/>\r\n<ol>\r\n<li>Terriestial producers: they include the grasses, trees, shrub, etc.</li>\r\n<li>Aquatic producers: examples are phytoplankton( spirogyra), sea weeds and water lily</li></ol><br/>\r\n<h3>Heterotrophs:</h3> <p>they are animals that cannot manufacture thier own food. They depend directly or indirectly on autotrophs for thier food and they are called â€œconsumersâ€ or â€œdecomposersâ€. </p><br/>\r\n,p>Animals that feed directly on green plants are called herbivores or primary consumers( primary producers) while animals that feed on primary consumers are called carnivores or secondary consumers and those that feed on secondary consumers are called tertiary comsumers. Heterotrophs can be divided into two as shown below:</p>\r\n<ol>\r\n<li>Terrestrial consumers: examples are caterpillars, toads, cows, etc.</li><br/>\r\n<li>Aquatic consumers: examples are water fleas, tadpole, larvae of insects and fishes.</li></ol><br/>\r\n<h3><b>Decomposers:</b></h3><br/><p> they are organisms that feed on dead organisms and decayed organic matter and release simple chemical compound which plants can be absorbed and use again. Examples of decomposers are insects such as termites, larvae of housefly, bacterial and fungi.</p> <br/>  ', '<ol>\r\n<li>Explain briefly on how biotic and abiotic interact in their natural enviroment</li><br/>\r\n<li>List and explain the two major abiotic factors that lead to the formation of an ecosystem.</li><br/>\r\n<li>What is the maor importance of biotic and abiotic factors?</li></ol>\r\n  ', '<p>from the concept taught, students should know that:</p><br/>\r\n<ol>\r\n<li>Biotic and abiotic components interact with one another in natural environment</li><br/>\r\n<li>Rainfall and temperature are the two important major abiotic factors that lead to the formation of an ecosystem</li><br/>\r\n<li>The importance of the biotic and abiotic factors is shown in their feeding relationships.</li></ol>\r\n  ', '<h2><b>Summary</b></h2><br/>\r\n<p>An ecosystem is a functional unit in nature. It consist of biotic and abiotic factors. Examples of the biotic factors are plants and animals while that of the abiotic factors are rainfall, temperature, sunlight, PH value wind. Among the examples of abiotic factors, rainfall and temperature determined the formation of an ecosystem.</p> <br/>\r\n<p>There are three components of an ecosystem namely:</p>\r\n<ol>\r\n<li>The autotrophs</li>\r\n<li>The heterotrophs, and </li>\r\n<li>The decomposers</li></ol>\r\n<p>The antotrophs manufactured their own food while the heterptrophs depends on antotrophs for survival and the decomposers acted on the dead organisms and decayed organic matter thereby supplying nutrients to the autotrophs for growth.</p>  ', '  ', 1, ''),
(5, 5, 'The modification of structures in carnivores as digestive system', '<h2>introduction</h2>\r\n<p>The various parts of carnivores animals such as dog are modified differently as that of man to perform the process of digestion. In dog, food digest the same way as in man but a the structures of dog varies with that of man due to the nature of food they feed on.</p>\r\n<p>Man eats plants and animals and they are said to be omnivores while dogs eats flesh which classified them as a carnivores. They (dogs-carnivores) capture and kill their preys as well as tearing off the flesh with their structurally adapted strong, curved and pointed tee4th. Food digest easily in carnivores than in omnivores because the alimentary canal is short and also due to the content of food is highly rich in protein. Breaking down of food in carnivores is the movement of jaws up and down. Below is the dentition formula of a dog and that of man (carnivores and omnivores). </p><br/>\r\n\r\n<p>Each of the four types of teeth such as incisors, canines, premolars and molars started with the initial letter in the dental formula and the total number of teeth is 32 when the total number of teeth in the dental formula is multiply by two. The 32 set of teeth is present in an adult and is called permanent teeth but in children, the total number of teeth is 20 called milk teeth or deciduous teeth because the molars which is the last set is absent in children. </p><br/>\r\n<p>Dental formula of carnivoresâ€™ e.g dog is shown below. </p><br/>\r\n\r\n<p>Therefore, a dog (carnivores) has 42 set of teeth.</p> <br/>\r\n', '<p>at the end of the lesson, students should be able to:\r\n<ol>\r\n<li>Explain briefly on how digestion takes place in carnivores.</li>\r\n<li>Describe briefly the role of the stomach indigestion.</li>\r\n<li>Describe on how the parts of carnivores are modified for digestion.</li>\r\n<li>Compare and contrast the digestion and mechanisms in carnivores and omnivores.</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n</p>\r\n', '<h3>>Step I</h3>\r\n<p>Carnivores are animals that feed on flesh only, when they capture and kill their preys as well as tearing off the flesh with their strong curved and pointed teeth. They break the flesh down by the action movement of the jaws up and down and the food moves down to the stomach, in the stomach, the foods digests easily and faster due to:</p>\r\n<ol>\r\n<li>The alimentary canal of carnivores is short.</li>\r\n<li>The food they feed on is highly rich in protein, but the digestion in man takes several hours because some many enzymes have to act on the food and also they have long alimentary canal.</li></ol>\r\n\r\n<h3>Step 2</h3>\r\n<p>The stomach is the site of digestion in vertebrate animals (animals with back bones). In man, when food gets to the stomach, several enzymes such as pepsin, rennin, hydrochloric acid, mucus, all are contain in the gastric juice acted upon the food before digestion. The digestion of food in the stomach can be said to be temporarily before getting to the small intestine where final digestion tales place.</p> <br/>\r\n\r\n<h3>Step III</h3>\r\n<p>Carnivoreâ€™s teeth having the following dentition formula</p><br/>\r\n<p>Their canines are strong, curved and pointed which enable them to seize and kill their prey as well as tearing their flesh. They do not keep food for long in their mouth as that of man because their intestines are short which allow food content highly rich in protein to be easily digest.<p> <br/>\r\n<h3>Step IV</h3>\r\n<p>Carnivores are animals that eat meat (flesh) only while omnivores are animals that eat plant and meat (flesh). The following are the similarities and differences between them.</p> <br/>\r\n<h3>Similarities</h3>\r\n<p>Possession of teeth for tearing and cutting food.</p> <br/>\r\n<p>Differences between carnivores and omnivores</p><br/>\r\n<table border="1">\r\n<tr><td><center>Carnivores</center></td><td><center>Omnivores</center></td></tr>\r\n<tr><td>They are flesh eaters e.g dog</td><td>They are plants and animal eaters e.g man<td></tr>\r\n<tr><td>Digestion is faster</td><td>Digestion is slow<td></tr>\r\n<tr><td>Canines are highly developed</td><td>Canines are not highly developed.<td></tr>\r\n<tr><td>Possession of short intestine </td><td>Possession of long intestine<td></tr>\r\n<tr><td>Only mechanical digestion takes place</td><td>Both mechanical and chemical digestion takes place.<td></tr>\r\n<tr><td>Dental number is more</td><td>Dental number is less.<td></tr>\r\n</table>\r\n', '<ol>\r\n<li>Write the dental formula of </li>\r\n(a)carnivores	<br/>	\r\n(b)omnivores	<br/>	\r\n\r\n<li>Write three differences between carnivores and omnivores in related to digestion processes.</li></ol>\r\n', '', '<b>Summary</b>\r\n<p>Various parts of carnivoresâ€™ animals perform different functions which differs with that of man. Digestion in carnivores is the same process as in man but their structures varies due to the nature or types of feed they eat. Carnivores eats flesh while omnivores eats flesh (meat) and plants. </p><br/>\r\n<p>Digestion in carnivores is faster while that of omnivores is slow because of the difference in their alimentary canal for being long and short respectively.</p> <br/>\r\n<p>The dental number of carnivores is higher than that of the omnivores (42 to 32 respectively) </p><br/>\r\n<p>Mechanically digestion takes place in the digestion process of carnivores due to the absence of enzymes to act on it but digestion in omnivores is both mechanically and chemical because various enzymes acted upon the food before final digestion. </p><br/>\r\n', '', 1, '');

